-- Japan Has One Reactor With 3% of Total Capacity Online
-- B y   Y u j i   O k a d a
-- 2012-07-02T03:11:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-02/japan-has-one-reactor-with-3-of-total-capacity-online-table-.html
Japan  has one of its 50 reactors
operating with a capacity of 1,180 megawatts, or 3 percent of
the total, according to data compiled by Bloomberg News.  Kansai Electric Power Co. (9503)  restarted the No. 3 reactor at
its Ohi nuclear power plant in western Japanâ€™s Fukui prefecture
yesterday, ending a two-month period for the country without an
operating reactor.  The No. 3 unit reached so-called criticality at 6 a.m.
today after the operation was resumed at 9 p.m. yesterday. The
plant is scheduled to generate electricity as early as July 4.
The utility plans to restart the 1,180-megawatt No. 4 reactor at
the plant as early as July 17.  The following table shows the status of the 50 reactors
with capacity of 46,148 megawatts operated by Japanese power
companies. Capacity figures are in megawatts.  
Sources: Hokkaido Electric, Tohoku Electric, Tokyo Electric,
Chubu Electric, Hokuriku Electric,  Kansai Electric , Chugoku
Electric, Shikoku Electric, Kyushu Electric, Japan Atomic Power.  To contact the reporter on this story:
